comments.content:
@oque -I’m consdering it because I’m seriosuly sick of arial, georgia, verdana and tahoma, which seems to be all websites come in these days (although I’m not a designer, I just do the xhtml/css/javascript/php...)

@Bert Vanderveen -I think a script can work. If you have a look at Calgary script at [http://www.sudtipos.com/fonts/90](http://web.archive.org/web/20100103041533/http:/www.sudtipos.com/fonts/90 "http://www.sudtipos.com/fonts/90"), I think it it is fun, playful and would stand out among the normal corporate-y looks.  
I think making a website should be fun, for both the client and for me. I used to work in a big agency and for a lot of very, eh, boring clients. If candy script would scare them off then great.  
And it could work, take a look at Morphix for example [http://www.morphix.si/#home](http://web.archive.org/web/20100103041533/http:/www.morphix.si/#home "http://www.morphix.si/#home")  
As I said, I wanted a script font because it looks human made rather than computer made. I handcode everything, I do not use templates. I want to emphasize this.
